                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d596">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 765.72112/3198</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">British Embassy</gloss> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<hi rend="italic">Received</hi>
                        <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-12-06">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 6, 1916</hi>
                        </date>.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The American Ambassador in London having suggested the desirability of some
                    explanation of the principles on which the policy of the British Government is
                    based in dealing with the question of the supply of bunker coal, the following
                    memorandum has been drawn up for public information:</p>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>His Majesty’s Government have for some time past found it necessary, owing to
                        the shortage and increasing scarcity of tonnage, to make special
                        arrangements at British ports and coaling stations abroad whereby coaling
                        facilities of all kinds should be reserved for vessels belonging to British
                        and Allied owners and to neutral owners who have undertaken to utilize their
                        vessels in such a way that British or Allied interests are benefitted. His
                        Majesty’s Government are in fact unable to guarantee that facilities can be
                        provided to other ships.</p>
                </quote>
            </div>
        </body>
